  "text": "TCF-1-deficient and -sufficient mice have comparable numbers of lin Ϫ DN1 cells (CD44 ϩ CD25 Ϫ ) ( Figure 1A -B). However, in contrast to wild type (63%), TCF-1-deficient lin Ϫ DN1 contain few cells (9%) expressing high levels of CD117 ( Figure 1C ), which defines early T-lineage progenitors (ETPs). [CITATION_1] Thus, the phenotype of TCF-1-deficient mice may be related in part to a reduced influx of progenitor cells from the bone marrow. TCF-1-deficient DN1 cells are predominantly CD127 ϩ and express intermediate levels of CD117 ( Figure 1C ). The former is consistent with the phenotype of late DN1 as well as DN2 cells. [CITATION_2] Indeed, many TCF-1-deficient DN1 cells express low levels of CD25. On the other hand bona fide CD25 hi DN2 cells are almost completely absent ( Figure 1A -B). DN3 cells (CD25 ϩ CD44 Ϫ ) were present even though at significantly reduced numbers as compared to wild-type animals ( Figure  1A -B). Some DN4 cells (CD25 Ϫ CD44 Ϫ ) were detectable in 3-week-old mice but almost completely absent thereafter ( Figure  1A -B). Thus, in addition to a depletion of DP cells, TCF-1-deficient mice display developmental blocks at the DN1 (CD25 Ϫ CD44 ϩ ) and DN3 stages. These data confirm and extend previous analyses, which were based on less stringent exclusion of lin ϩ cells. [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] ",
